<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-10-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-10-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="515" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d515">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Raikes</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Adee</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">British
                                        Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-10-01"><hi rend="italic">October 1,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Adee</hi>: I forwarded to Lord Lansdowne in
                            an official dispatch a copy of the report from the commanding officer of
                            the U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Philadelphia</hi>, inclosed in your
                            personal note of August 9, describing his readiness to protect British
                            interests at Panama in the absence of H. M. S. <hi rend="italic">Amphion</hi>. I have now great pleasure in asking you, by Lord
                            Lansdowne’s direction, to be so good as to convey to the commander of
                            the <hi rend="italic">Philadelphia</hi> an expression of the thanks of
                            His Majesty’s Government for his friendly attitude on this occasion.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Arthur S.
                            Raikes.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>